	<h3>Easy Output (Using BeanDisplay)</h3>
	
	To display a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaBeans">JavaBean</a> with very little effort, 
	use Tapestry's <code>BeanDisplay</code> component. Here it is displaying a JPA Entity Bean:<br/>
	
	<div class="eg">
		<t:beandisplay object="person"/>
	</div>
	
	The bean displayed above is a Person, retrieved from the database by PersonFinderService.<br/><br/>

	2 new things:<br/><br/>
	<ul>
		<li><code>BeanDisplay</code>  A component which is great for rapid prototyping, 
			and which can be used for more than that because its parameters let you exclude fields, 
			include fields, reorder fields, etc. Its styling can be overridden with CSS.</li>
		<li><code>@EJB</code>  A field annotation which injects a Java EE Session Bean. 
			JumpStart has contributed this annotation to the application. 
			An alternative is to use JPA or Hibernate directly, which Tapestry can do. 
			Both approaches are valid, and both have pros and cons. For more information see the @EJB example later.</li>
	</ul>	
	
	References: 
	<a href="http://people.apache.org/~hlship/t5api/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/corelib/components/BeanDisplay.html">BeanDisplay</a>,
